Italian Stocks: Ansaldo, Eni, Intesa, STMicro, UniCredit Shares Are Active

-- B y   F r a n c e s c a   C i n e l l i
-- 
2011-02-21T13:36:29Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-02-20/coin-erg-tamburi-investment-partners-italian-equity-preview.html
Italy’s benchmark  FTSE MIB Index 
dropped the most in six weeks, falling 494.22, or 2.1 percent,
to 22,564.81 at 2:03 p.m. in Milan.  The following stocks were among the most active in the
Italian market today.  Ansaldo SpA (STS IM) fell for a third day, dropping 3.2
percent to 10.45 euros. CA Cheuvreux reiterated a cautious
stance on Finmeccanica SpA’s railway technology unit with an
unchanged “underperform” rating, saying that the company is
“exposed” to Libya with “two significant orders in the
backlog.”  Banca Popolare di Milano Scrl (PMI IM) dropped 3 percent to
3.04 euros as banking shares were the worst performers in
Europe.  Banco Popolare SC  (BP IM) fell 3 percent to 2.63 euros.    Eni SpA  (ENI IM) sank 4.5 percent to 17.55 euros. “Eni is
the largest independent operator in Libya,” Equita SIM SpA said
in a note. “No problems at plants and operational activities
have been reported,” Eni said in a statement. Family members of
Eni workers are being relocated and repatriated, the company
said. Production continues as normal, it said.  Fiat SpA (F IM) dropped 2 percent to 6.94 euros, falling
for a second day. Kepler Capital Markets reiterated a “reduce”
rating on the carmaker after OAO Sollers and Fiat ended talks to
create a joint venture in Russia. The brokerage also said that
“we are negative on the story and remain firm in considering
the industrial plan targets as unrealistic from 2012 onwards.”    Impregilo SpA  (IPG IM) plummeted 5.2 percent to 2.33 euros,
the biggest loss since July 1. Equita said in a note that
Italy’s biggest builder has “projects worth 1 billion euros, or
about 11 percent of backlog” in Libya, Equita said.    Intesa Sanpaolo SpA  (ISP IM) dropped 2.8 percent to 2.46
euros, a third straight loss. Intermonte Sim SpA downgraded
Italy’s second-biggest bank to “neutral” from “outperform.”
The brokerage cited the stock’s recent performance.    STMicroelectronics NV  (STM IM) rose 1 percent to 9.48
euros, the best performance on the FTSE MIB Index. Europe’s
largest chipmaker had its price estimate lifted to 12 euros from
10 euros at Morgan Stanley.    UniCredit SpA  (UCG IM) fell 3.3 percent to 1.92 euros, the
biggest loss in almost four weeks. Fidentiis Equities said a
regime change in  Libya  is unlikely to trigger a disposal of the
Libyan Investment Authority’s stake in the bank.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Francesca Cinelli in Milan at 
 fcinelli@bloomberg.net .  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
David Merritt at   dmerritt1@bloomberg.net . 